1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,771
Start with the pattern Anthropic observed.

2
00:00:02,721 --> 00:00:12,028
The report analyzed nine thousand eight hundred thirty substantive, multi-turn Claude conversations and measured eleven collaboration behaviors that could be seen inside the chat.

3
00:00:12,028 --> 00:00:16,673
Artifact-producing conversations made up twelve point three percent of the sample.

4
00:00:16,673 --> 00:00:20,528
When people were building an artifact, they became more directive.

5
00:00:20,528 --> 00:00:24,721
Goal clarification rose by fourteen point seven percentage points.

6
00:00:24,721 --> 00:00:28,586
Specifying a format rose by fourteen point five points.

7
00:00:28,586 --> 00:00:34,865
Providing examples rose by thirteen point four points, and iteration rose by nine point seven points.

8
00:00:34,865 --> 00:00:38,230
But the evaluation side moved in the opposite direction.

9
00:00:38,230 --> 00:00:42,605
Identifying missing context fell by five point two percentage points.

10
00:00:42,605 --> 00:00:45,800
Fact checking fell by three point seven points.

11
00:00:45,800 --> 00:00:50,865
Asking the model to explain the basis for its reasoning fell by three point one points.

12
00:00:50,865 --> 00:00:52,509
Why might this happen?

13
00:00:52,509 --> 00:00:57,865
A polished artifact looks closer to completion, so the user may treat appearance as evidence.

14
00:00:57,865 --> 00:01:03,000
Some artifact tasks also reward function or aesthetics more than factual precision.

15
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:10,201
And some users may be testing the code, sharing the draft, or reviewing it elsewhere, where the study cannot see their evaluation.

16
00:01:10,201 --> 00:01:14,836
Those explanations matter because the findings are correlational, not causal.

17
00:01:14,836 --> 00:01:18,923
The study does not prove that polished output makes people less critical.

18
00:01:18,923 --> 00:01:25,980
It shows a reliable enough association to create a useful warning: completion cues can arrive before evaluation is complete.

19
00:01:25,980 --> 00:01:28,846
Use polish as a trigger, not a verdict.

20
00:01:28,846 --> 00:01:32,875
When an output looks finished, pause before praising or publishing it.

21
00:01:32,875 --> 00:01:38,557
Ask what claim, assumption, dependency, or consequence is hardest to see from the surface.

22
00:01:38,557 --> 00:01:43,528
First, polished presentation can arrive before critical evaluation is complete.

23
00:01:43,528 --> 00:01:48,326
Second, artifact conversations show more direction but less visible checking.

24
00:01:48,326 --> 00:01:52,403
Third, use polish as a review trigger rather than proof of quality.
